Scotland’s independent schools maintain outstanding academic results and this continued 2018 with another set of outstanding test results, which are only strengthened by individual and collective advances in sports, arts, music and other social engagements.
With up to 30,000 students in Scotland, schools, represented by the Scottish Council of Independent Schools (SCIS), strive to provide the best possible service for their students and their parents.
Independent schools strive to prepare their students for further education, their chosen career and their role as global citizens.
As an educational sector that can design and implement customized curriculums, we see that modern languages continue to be popular and requested topics at schools.
Nelson Mandela said, \"If you talk to a man in a language he understands, it goes to his head.
If you talk to him in his own language, it goes to his heart.
It’s a powerful reminder that we can’t just rely on English when we create relationships and trust with people from other countries.
This year’s test results show that language is at the top of the list, with a maximum number of approved results within independent schools.
A total of 68 percent of students who studied foreign languages received A in the final exam Higher Grade.
Data collected from SCIS 74 member schools showed that 72 per cent of students who studied Mandarin received an A in Higher Grade, and 72 per cent of those who studied German, 69 per cent of those who studied French and 63 per cent of those who studied Spanish also received an A.
This shows that independent schools in Scotland support foreign languages as crucial skills that children and young people will undoubtedly need in the future.
Language as a subject choice is now considered to be as important as natural knowledge, technology, engineering and mathematics on curriculums in independent schools and beyond.
A study conducted by the UK Commission for Employment and Skills in 2014 concluded that employers had difficulty filling their vacancies, with 17 percent attributed to a lack of language skills.
With this said, language skills become all the more necessary to prepare young people for their future careers.
With more and more future jobs that require language skills, these skills become necessary in a globalized world.
Regardless of the career choice, they will have a real advantage in the future if they have adopted a second language.
Being able to communicate directly with people from other countries, automatically provides a multilingual person with a competitive advantage.
According to a survey of more than 4,000 adult Brits published by YouGov 2013, 75% said that they could not speak a foreign language well enough to hold a conversation in it, and where French was the only language that came up in total in a two-digit percentage (15 percent).
Therefore, it is so important to invest in language teaching for our children.
Being able to speak multiple languages, especially those used in developing countries, gives your child a better chance of finding meaningful employment in the future.
In Scotland, each school will teach different combinations of languages.
A number of schools will focus on the more classic modern languages, while others will teach languages that are considered most important to the UK for 2020, such as Chinese or Japanese.
Regardless of your child’s interest, there will always be a number of languages to choose from in independent schools, with teachers who are specialists in this area.
Scottish independent schools strive to provide a learning environment that will prepare children and have them with the skills necessary to succeed, regardless of what the future has in place.
In a global economic environment, it is undoubtedly a language that continues to be crucial for the country's future, so it needs to reflect in education.
In fact, modern languages should really be regarded as “international communication skills”
Independent schools will continue to offer this choice, diversity and excellence to Scotland’s young people.
