Harvard students take courses to get enough rest
A new course at Harvard University this year has led all doctoral students to improve their sleep habits in an effort to combat the growing macho culture to study through caffeine-filled “dysts”
An academic study found that students at the world’s leading universities are often ignorant when it comes to the basics of how to take care of themselves.
Charles Czeisler, Professor of Sleep Medicine at Harvard Medical School and a specialist at Brigham and Women's Hospital, designed the course, which he considers to be the first in his kind in the United States.
He was inspired to start the course after talking about the impact of lack of sleep on learning.
“At the end of it, a girl came up to me and said, ‘Why don’t I know this until now, during my last year?’
She said that no one had ever told her about the importance of sleep - which surprised me, he told The Telegraph.
The course, which was organised for the first time this year, explains to students the importance of how good sleep habits help academic and athletic performance, as well as improve their general well-being.
Paul Barreira, Professor of Psychiatry at Harvard Medical School and Executive Director of University Health Services, said that the university decided to introduce the course after discovering that students suffered from severe sleep shortages during the week.
The hour-long course includes a range of interactive tasks.
In part of the course there is a picture of a student room, where students click on coffee cups, curtains, trainers and books to learn about the effects of caffeine and light, how athletic performance is affected by sleep shortages and the importance of good sleep habits.
In another part, participants learn how long-term sleep shortages can increase the risk of heart attacks, stroke, depression, and cancer.
A map of campus, with interactive icons, encourages participants to think about their daily routine.
“We know that it will not change students’ behavior directly.
But we believe that they have the right to know - just as one has the right to know about the health effects of choosing to smoke cigarettes, - added Professor Czeisler.
The culture of pride in “deepness” still exists, he says, adding that modern technology and constant pressure on students meant that sleep lack was a growing problem.
To ensure that you have enough sleep, of good quality, should be the student’s secret weapons — to combat stress, fatigue and anxiety, he said — even to avoid weight gain because insomnia puts the brain in hunger and makes them constantly hungry.
Raymond So, a 19-year-old Californian who studies chemical and physical biology, helped Professor Czeisler design the course and has read one of his courses last year during his first year at Harvard.
He said the course was an eye opener and inspired him to campaign for a campus-wide course.
He hopes that the next step is to ask all doctoral students to complete a similar study program before starting their studies at the high-performance institution.
Professor Czeisler recommended that students consider setting an alarm for when to lay down and when to wake up and be aware of the harmful effects of “blue light” issued by electronic screens and LED lighting, which can cause you to turn around on the clock, leading to insom problems.
